{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti (also known as the *Laws of Manu*), Chapter 7.**\n\nThis chapter personifies the rod of punishment (*Daṇḍa*) as the creation of the Lord (identified with Brahmā), calling it \"his own son\" who embodies *Dharma* itself from the beginning as protector of all beings.[^1] It further declares *Daṇḍa* to be *Dharma* incarnate.[^2] The text warns that without the king's diligent application of punishment, \"the stronger would roast the weaker like fish on a spit.\"[^3]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 7*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-73f910).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 7*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-48dedc).\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 7*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-d56424).",
